BEGIN_TEXT
Computing Mass: if the density of an object at a point is given by \(\delta\) then the Mass of an object R is 
$BCENTER
M = \(\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int\delta\hskip{2pt} dV\)
$ECENTER
Center of Mass: if the density of an object at a point is given by \(\delta\) then the center of mass is a point \(\left(\overline{x},\overline{y},\overline{z}\right)\)  
$BR
\(\overline{x}=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int x\delta\hskip{2pt} dV} {\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int\delta\hskip{2pt} dV}
=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int x\delta\hskip{2pt} dV} {{\rm M}}
\)
$BR
\(\overline{y}=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int y\delta\hskip{2pt} dV} {\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int\delta\hskip{2pt} dV}
=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int y\delta\hskip{2pt} dV} {{\rm M}}
\)
$BR
\(\overline{z}=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int z\delta\hskip{2pt} dV} {\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int\delta\hskip{2pt} dV}
=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int z\delta\hskip{2pt} dV} {{\rm M}}
\)
$BR
If the density of an object is constant the \(\delta\)'s can be factored out of the numerator and denominator and will cancel:
$BR
\(\overline{x}=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int x\hskip{2pt} dV} {\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int\hskip{2pt} dV}
=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int x\hskip{2pt} dV} {{\rm V}}
\)
$BR
\(\overline{y}=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int y\hskip{2pt} dV} {\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int\hskip{2pt} dV}
=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int y\hskip{2pt} dV} {{\rm V}}
\)
$BR
\(\overline{z}=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int z\hskip{2pt} dV} {\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int\hskip{2pt} dV}
=\frac{\int\!\!\int\limits_R\!\!\int z\hskip{2pt} dV} {{\rm V}}
\)
$BR

 In this case the center of mass is called the centroid.
END_TEXT


